\c 22
\s1 Raja Moab memanggil Bileam
\p
\v 1 Bangsa Israel berangkat lagi dan berkemah di dataran Moab, di seberang sungai Yordan dekat Yerikho.
\p
\v 2 Balak raja orang Moab, anaknya Zipor mendengar apa yang sudah dilakukan orang Israel terhadap orang Amori.
\v 3 Orang Moab menjadi gentar dan takut terhadap orang Israel karena jumlah mereka yang sangat banyak itu.
\p
\v 4 Orang Moab berkata kepada para pemimpin Midian, "Gerombolan orang ini akan segera mengahncurkan segala sesuatu yang ada di sekeliling kita, seperti lembu jantan memakan rumput di padang." Adapun Balak adalah raja orang Moab,
\p
\v 5 mengirim utusan kepada Bileam anak Beor, yang tinggal di Petor dekat sungai Efrat di daerah Amau. Mereka membawa pesan ini dari Balak, "Suatu bangsa datang dari Mesir, orangnya menyebar kemana-mana dan mengancam siap menyerang dan mengambil alih tanah kami.
\v 6 Mereka lebih kuat dari kami. Tolong datang dan kutuklah mereka untuk kami. Barangkali kami dapat mengalahkan mereka dan mengusir mereka dari negeri ini. Karena aku tahu orang yang kamu berkati akan mendapat berkat; dan orang yang kamu kutuk akan mendapat kutuk."
\v 7 Lalu berangkatlah para pemimpin orang Moab dan orang Midian itu dengan membawa upah untuk Bileam supaya dia mau mengutuk orang Israel. Sesudah sampai kepada Bileam, mereka menyampaikan kepadanya pesan dari raja Balak.
\p
\v 8 Berkatalah Bileam kepada mereka, "Tinggallah di sini pada malam ini dan besok aku akan memberikan jawaban kepadamu sesuai dengan yang difirmakan TUHAN kepadaku." Maka tinggallah para pemimpin Moab itu di tempat Bileam.
\p
\v 9 Lalu Allah datang kepada Bileam dan bertanya, "Siapakah orang-orang yang tinggal bersamamu itu?"
\p
\v 10 Jawab Bileam kepada Allah, "Mereka utusan Raja Balak dari Moab untuk membawa pesan kepada saya tentang,
\v 11 suatu bangsa datang dari Mesir dan mereka sudah menyebar kemana-mana. Raja Balak meminta saya mengutuk bangsa itu supaya dia bisa mengalahkan dan mengusir mereka.”
\p
\v 12 Kata Allah kepada Bileam, "Jangan pergi bersama-sama dengan mereka dan jangan kutuk bangsa itu karena mereka sudah Aku berkati."
\p
\v 13 Maka keesokan harinya Bileam berkata kepada utusan-utusan Balak itu, "Pulanglah ke negerimu sebab TUHAN tidak mengizinkan aku pergi bersama dengan kamu.”
\p
\v 14 Lalu kembalilah mereka kepada Balak dan memberitahukan bahwa Bileam menolak untuk datang bersama dengan mereka.
\p
\v 15 Tetapi Balak mengirim lebih banyak lagi utusan yang jabatannya lebih tinggi dari utusan pertama.
\v 16 Sesudah mereka sampai kepada Bileam, mereka menyampaikan pesan Raja Balak kepadanya, "Aku memohon jangan menolak untuk datang kepadaku,
\v 17 aku akan memberimu upah yang banyak dan apapun yang kamu minta akan aku berikan. Datanglah dan kutuklah bangsa itu untukku.”
\p
\v 18 Tetapi Bileam menjawab, "Meskipun Balak memberiku semua perak dan emas yang ada di istana, aku tidak akan melanggar perintah TUHAN, Allahku bahkan dalam hal sekecil sekalipun.
\v 19 Silahkan tinggal di sini malam ini, seperti yang dilakukan utusan yang pertama. Aku ingin tahu apakah masih ada yang ingin dikatakan TUHAN kepadaku.”
\p
\v 20 Lalu pada malam itu, datanglah Allah kepada Bileam dan berkata, "orang-orang itu datang untuk meminta kamu pergi bersama dengan mereka. Jadi besiaplah dan pergi dengan mereka, tetapi lakukanlah sesuai yang Aku perintahkan kepadamu.”
\s1
\p
\v 21 So the next morning, Balaam put a saddle on his donkey and he departed\add with two of his servants\add* along with the men from Moab.
\v 22 \add Even though God had given Balaam permission to go, he was stillangry\add*. So he sent one of his angels to Balaam. This angel stood in the road to block Balaam's path. As Balaam and the two servants were riding on their donkeys,
\v 23 Balaam's donkey saw the angel. The angel was standing in the road and was holding a sword in his hand,\add but Balaam did not see him\add*.
\p Balaam's donkey turned off the road into a field. So Balaam struck the donkey and forced it to go back onto the road.
\v 24 Then the angel stood in a place where the road was very narrow, between two vineyards, with walls on each side of the road.
\v 25 When the donkey saw the angel standing there, it walked very close to the wall\add to try to get past the angel\add*. As a result, it bashed Balaam's foot against the wall. So Balaam struck the donkey again.
\p
\v 26 Then the angel went further along the road and stood at a place that was extremely narrow, with the result that the donkey could not get past at all.
\v 27 This time, when the donkey saw the angel, it lay down \add on theground\add* with Balaam sitting on top of it. Balaam became extremely angry, and he struck the donkey again with his walking stick.
\v 28 Then Yahweh enabled the donkey to speak! It said to Balaam, “What bad thing have I done to you that caused you to strike me three times?”
\p
\v 29 Balaam shouted, “I struck you because you have caused me to appear to be foolish! If I had a sword with me, I would kill you!”
\p
\v 30 But the donkey answered, “I am your own donkey [RHQ], the one that you have always ridden! Have I ever done anything like this previously?”
\p Balaam said, “No.”
\p
\v 31 Then Yahweh enabled Balaam to see the angel standing on the road, holding a sword in his hand. Balaam\add realized that it was an angel and\add* prostrated himself on the ground in front of the angel.
\p
\v 32 The angel asked him, “Why did you strike your donkey three times [RHQ]? I have come to block your path because what you are planning to do is wrong.
\v 33 Three times your donkey saw me and turned away from me. If it had not done that, I would certainly have killed you already, but I would have allowed the donkey to live.”
\p
\v 34 Then Balaam said to the angel, “I have sinned. But I did not realize that you were standing there, trying to block my path. So if you do not want me to continue going, I will return home.”
\p
\v 35 But the angel replied, “I will allow you to go with these men, but you must say only what I tell you to say!”
\p So Balaam went on with the leaders whom Balak \add had sent\add*.
\p
\v 36 When King Balak heard that Balaam was coming, he went to meet him at a Moab town alongside the Arnon\add River\add* that was at the border of his own land.
\v 37 \add When he arrived where\add* Balaam was, he said to him, “I sent you [RHQ] a message saying that you should comeimmediately [RHQ]! Why did you not come? \add Did you think that\add* I was not able to pay you a lot of money for coming?”
\p
\v 38 Balaam replied, “I have come here now, but I am not able to say anything\add that I want to\add*. I will say only the words that God tells me to say [MTY].”
\p
\v 39 Then Balaam went with Balak to Kiriath-Huzoth \add town\add*.
\v 40 There Balak killed some cattle and sheep as sacrifices, and offered\add parts of the meat\add* to Balaam and the leaders who were with him.
\v 41 \add They slept there\add*, and the next morning Balak took Balaam part way up\add the mountain\add* to Bamoth-Baal \add village\add*. From there, they could see some of the Israeli people who were down below.